nameBreakdown.genus: abiēs (Latin, noun), meaning 'silver fir [specifically Abies alba]'. Commonly known as fir, a genus of various species of evergreen coniferous trees. Learn more about Abies.

speciesNativeRange: The states of Oregon, California, Utah, Colorado, Arizona, and New Mexico in the United States. Also Northern Mexico and the state of Baja California in Mexico.
description: Forms a tall, pyramidal tree with blue-grey needles. A slow grower that thrives in areas with long winters and cool summers. When established, will tolerate dry soils and some drought, but grows best in moist, well-drained soils. Does not grow well in heavy clay soils or constantly wet soils. Ideal in containers or as a bonsai subject. Great as a Christmas tree.

nameBreakdown.family: legume, pea, or bean family, a family of flowering trees, shrubs, and herbaceous plants. Learn more about Fabaceae.

Commonly known as wattle or acacia, a genus of various trees and shrubs. Learn more about Acacia.
nameBreakdown.species: baileyana (Latinised), honouring the botanist Frederick Manson Bailey (1827 - 1915). Learn more about Acacia baileyana.

speciesNativeRange: The state of New South Wales in Australia.
description: Grey-green ferny leaves, with new growth emerging in a striking purple colour. A mass of gold-yellow flowers through winter. Grows best in dry or stony soil with good drainage. Drought tolerant once established. An outstanding foliage and flower tree.

speciesNativeRange: The states of New South Wales, Queensland, and Victoria in Australia.
description: A graceful, spreading, bushy tree with an open form and narrow leaves. Pale-yellow, fragrant flowers in fluffy balls through late-winter and spring. Tolerates heavy clay soils and periodically wet soils. Will tolerate dry soil in a garden situation, but prefers moist to wet soil. Can be used for windbreaks, hedges, and screens.

speciesNativeRange: The state of Victoria in Australia.
description: Sold in New Zealand in a dwarf, weeping form. Fast, graceful grower with pendulous branches. Prefers moist, well-drained soils but will tolerate occasional drought. Fragrant, pale-yellow flowers in spring. Can be used for bonsai.

speciesNativeRange: The states of South Australia, Queensland, New South Wales, and Victoria in Australia.
description: Prized for its beautiful marbled timber. Quick-growing, hardy shade and shelter tree. Dense, round-headed tree with pale-yellow flowers appearing from late-winter to early-spring. Tolerates high rainfall. Prefers moist soils, but will tolerate some drought. Has a shallow root system with dense, surface feeder roots. Fixes atmospheric nitrogen into the soil. Good for hedges, screens, and shelterbelts.

speciesNativeRange: The provinces of Shandong, Gansu, Guangdong, and Sichuan in China. Also Taiwan and Japan.
description: Hardy maple good for street plantings and as a shade tree. Upright growth habit when young, maturing to a rounded canopy. Copper-red new growth, with leaves turning green in summer. Autumn leaves of vivid red, apricot, and yellow. Grows best in full-sun in well-drained soils. Tolerates wind and is somewhat drought-tolerant once established. Has a moderate tolerance for coastal sites. Will tolerate air pollution. Great for bonsai.

description: Species from Western China. Large, deeply-lobed leaves emerge bronze-purple and mature to olive-green with prominent veins. Upright, spreading habit. Glowing yellow and orange autumn leaves. Grows best in full sun in moist, well-drained soils.

speciesNativeRange: Much of Europe, including Denmark, Poland, Belarus, England, and Scotland. Also southwest Asia from Turkey to the Caucasus Mountains and north Africa in the Atlas Mountains.
description: Compact tree with a dense, round canopy, and somewhat corky bark. Small leaves with rounded lobes are dark-green in summer, turning a beautiful yellow in autumn. Prefers moist, well-drained soils. Tolerates air pollution, dry soils, and clay soils. Green, inconspicuous flowers in early to mid-spring. Tolerates strong winds and coastal sites. Good for bonsai.

otherCommonNames: Hair-foot Maple, Hosoe-Kaede, Ashiboso-urinoki, Red Snakebark Maple, Kyushu Maple

description: Young spring foliage is bright-yellow with orange-red margins. Foliage fades to light-green in summer. Autumn leaves are bright-yellow. Can tolerate periods of drought, but prefers moist, well-drained soils. Has a shallow root system. Avoid planting in windy, exposed areas.

description: Stunning features throughout the year. Pink, new stems with green leaves in spring and variegated green leaves in summer. Orange-red leaves in autumn. Grows best in part-shade in moist, well-drained soil, sheltered from strong winds. Striped bark is a feature.

description: A tidy and slender, erect-growing Chinese maple. Beautiful chestnut-brown, smooth bark peels in thin strips revealing brighter, cinnamon-red wood beneath. Comes into leaf in late-spring, evading a lot of the damaging spring winds. Fiery-red and orange autumn leaves. Prefers moist, well-drained soils and grows well in clay soils. Does not tolerate drought or dry soils. Great for bonsai.

The leaves are light to robust-green from early spring through summer, changing in autumn to orange-yellow and bright-red. Prefers moist, well-drained soils in part-shade. Will grow in full sun, but leaves may scorch in hot summers. Protect from strong winds. New foliage tends to come out early in spring and can be damaged by late-frosts.

Tolerates air pollution, drought, and occasionally water-logged soils once established. Cold hardy.

nameBreakdown.species: glūtinōsa (Latin, adjective), meaning 'gluey, sticky', in reference to the sticky young buds and shoots of this species. Learn more about Alnus glutinosa.

description: Elegant tree with outspreading branches. Fine and deeply-cut, green leaves. Tolerant of wet soils. Looks great planted next to water. Yellow-green catkins are a source of pollen for bees in early to mid-spring. Fixes nitrogen in the soil, so good for improving soil conditions for other plants.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: alnus (Latin, noun), meaning 'alder'. Commonly known as alder, a genus of trees and shrubs. Learn more about Alnus.
nameBreakdown.species: glūtinōsa (Latin, adjective), meaning 'gluey, sticky', in reference to the sticky young buds and shoots of this species. Learn more about Alnus glutinosa.

description: Conical-growing tree with finely-cut, green leaves. Tolerates wet and windy sites. Yellow-green catkins are a source of pollen for bees in early to mid-spring. Fixes nitrogen in the soil, so good for improving soil conditions for other plants.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: alnus (Latin, noun), meaning 'alder'. Commonly known as alder, a genus of trees and shrubs. Learn more about Alnus.
nameBreakdown.species: incāna (Latin, adjective), meaning 'quite grey, hoary (white, grey-white)', in reference to the colour of the underside of the leaves. Learn more about Alnus incana.

description: A large, conical tree with yellow leaves in spring, maturing to yellow-green in summer before turning yellow in autumn. The young branches are orange-yellow, providing a spectacular show in winter. Red-pink catkins are a source of pollen for bees in early to mid-spring. Fixes nitrogen in the soil, so good for improving soil conditions for other plants.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: alnus (Latin, noun), meaning 'alder'. Commonly known as alder, a genus of trees and shrubs. Learn more about Alnus.
nameBreakdown.species: inokumae (Latinised), named after the Japanese botanist Taizo Inokuma (1904 - 1973). Learn more about Alnus inokumae.

description: A fast and straight-growing alder. Attractive, dark-green leaves. Great for wherever fast-growing screening trees are required. Tolerates wet sites. Yellow autumn leaves. Yellow-green catkins are a source of pollen for bees in early to mid-spring. Fixes nitrogen in the soil, so good for improving soil conditions for other plants.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: alnus (Latin, noun), meaning 'alder'. Commonly known as alder, a genus of trees and shrubs. Learn more about Alnus.
nameBreakdown.species: jorullensis (Latinised), in reference to the report by Alexander von Humboldt, Aimé Bonpland, and Carl Sigismund Kunth (1817) that the original specimen of this species was collected from the volcano El Jorullo in Michoacán, Mexico. Learn more about Alnus jorullensis.

description: Fast-growing. Has long, green, toothed leaves. Can be easily pruned to any shape. Excellent as a dense screen. Yellow-green catkins are a source of pollen for bees in early to mid-spring. Fixes nitrogen in the soil, so good for improving soil conditions for other plants.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: alnus (Latin, noun), meaning 'alder'. Commonly known as alder, a genus of trees and shrubs. Learn more about Alnus.
nameBreakdown.species: rubra (Latin, adjective), meaning 'red', in reference to the orange-red inner bark of this species. Learn more about Alnus rubra.

description: Slender, pyramidal form. Red buds reveal red-green catkins in spring. Inner bark is orange-red. Green leaves are blue-green beneath. Hardy. Tolerates moist soils. Catkins are a source of pollen for bees in early to mid-spring. Fixes nitrogen in the soil, so good for improving soil conditions for other plants.

nameBreakdown.family: rose family, a family of mostly deciduous (but some evergreen), flowering herbs, shrubs, and trees. Learn more about Rosaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: amelanchier, derived from the French amélanchier, meaning 'serviceberry', in reference to Amelanchier ovalis. Commonly known as shadbush, shadwood, shadblow, serviceberry, juneberry, or sugarplum, a genus of deciduous shrubs and small trees. Learn more about Amelanchier.
nameBreakdown.species: canadēnsis (Latin, adjective), meaning 'Canadian, of or relating to Canada', in reference to this species' native geographical location. Learn more about Amelanchier canadensis.

description: Compact, neat tree with a rounded head. Bronze new spring leaves turn a stunning red, yellow, and orange in autumn. Lacy, white, drooping flower clusters from late-winter to late-spring. Edible berries in early-summer. Berries start red and then turn purple when ripe and ready to eat.

nameBreakdown.family: araucaria family, an ancient family of coniferous trees. Learn more about Araucariaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: araucaria, derived from Arauco, the name of a province in southern Chile where trees from this genus were first discovered. A genus of evergreen coniferous trees. Learn more about Araucaria.
nameBreakdown.species: araucana, derived from the native Araucanian Mapuche of Chile who used the nuts (seeds) of this species. Learn more about Araucaria araucana.

description: Slow-growing. Pyramidal growth habit when young, spreading out with age. Has leathery, spiky, triangle-shaped leaves on widely-spaced branches.

nameBreakdown.family: araucaria family, an ancient family of coniferous trees. Learn more about Araucariaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: araucaria, derived from Arauco, the name of a province in southern Chile where trees from this genus were first discovered. A genus of evergreen coniferous trees. Learn more about Araucaria.
nameBreakdown.species: heterophylla (Latin, adjective), derived from the Greek adjective ἕτερος (héteros, 'different') and noun φύλλον (phúllon, 'leaf'), meaning 'different leaves', in reference to the variation in the leaves between young and mature plants of this species. Learn more about Araucaria heterophylla.

description: Stately, erect tree with a pyramidal form. Ideal hardy coastal tree. Enduring tree for large spaces. Can be kept small in a container.

otherCommonNames: Canary Madrone, Canary Islands Strawberry Tree

nameBreakdown.family: heath or heather family, a family of flowering herbs, shrubs, and trees. Learn more about Ericaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: arbutus (Latin, noun), meaning 'strawberry tree', in reference to Arbutus unedo. A genus of flowering plants. Learn more about Arbutus.
nameBreakdown.species: canariēnsis (Latin, adjective), meaning 'of or relating to the Canary Islands', in reference to this species' native geographical location. Learn more about Arbutus canariensis.

description: Has bold, green foliage. Large, upright panicles of white, bell-shaped flowers cover the tree in autumn to early-winter. They are a good source of pollen for bees. Green fruit appear in winter after the flowers and take almost a full year to ripen. The fruit change color through yellow to red and ripen when the next year's autumn flowers appear. Birds love the fruit. Has peeling, red-brown bark. Wind and heat tolerant.

otherCommonNames: Irish Strawberry Tree, Killarney Strawberry Tree, Cane Apple

nameBreakdown.family: heath or heather family, a family of flowering herbs, shrubs, and trees. Learn more about Ericaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: arbutus (Latin, noun), meaning 'strawberry tree', in reference to Arbutus unedo. A genus of flowering plants. Learn more about Arbutus.
nameBreakdown.species: unedō (Latin, noun), meaning 'strawberry tree', in reference to Arbutus unedo. There is a folk etymology of unedō by Pliny the Elder (AD 23/24 - 79) that it comes from the Latin numeral ūnum (one) and the verb edō (I eat), in supposed reference to the foul taste of the fruit so only one could be eaten at a time. Learn more about Arbutus unedo.

description: Very hardy to adverse conditions including coastal, heat, and cold. Small, white flowers in autumn and winter. Green fruit appear in winter after the flowers and take almost a full year to ripen. The fruit change color through yellow to red and ripen when the next year's autumn flowers appear. Birds love the fruit and the flowers are a good source of pollen for bees. Has peeling, red-brown bark.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of flowering trees and shrubs. Learn more about Elaeocarpaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: aristotelia (Latinised), named in honour of the Greek philosopher and polymath, Aristotle. A genus of flowering plants. Learn more about Aristotelia.
nameBreakdown.species: serrāta (Latin, adjective), meaning 'serrated, saw-toothed', in reference to the serrated edges of this species' leaves. Learn more about Aristotelia serrata.

description: Cream to rose-pink flowers in spring followed by dark-red to purple-black berries in summer that attract native birds. The leaves sometimes have pink-red undersides. Tolerates light-frosts and can be semi-evergreen in colder climates.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of flowering plants. Learn more about Asteliaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: astelia, derived from the Greek prefix ἀ (makes the sense of a word opposite to the word to which it is attached) and noun στήλη (stḗlē, 'upright rock, pillar, column'), meaning 'without a pillar/column', in reference to the apparent stemless condition of some species in this genus. A genus of flowering plants native to New Zealand, Australia, South America, and various islands in the Pacific, Indian, and South Atlantic oceans. Learn more about Astelia.
nameBreakdown.species: chathamica (Latinised), meaning 'of or relating to the Chatham Islands', in reference to this species' native geographical location. Learn more about Astelia chathamica.

description: Ornamental, clump-forming plant with broad, spiky, silver-green leaves which droop at their tips. Easily grown in full sun or semi-shade. Will tolerate both moist and dry sites. Dramatic in group plantings. Coastal hardy. Excellent in containers.

otherCommonNames: Mountain Astelia, Bush Flax, Bush Lily

nameBreakdown.family: a family of flowering plants. Learn more about Asteliaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: astelia, derived from the Greek prefix ἀ (makes the sense of a word opposite to the word to which it is attached) and noun στήλη (stḗlē, 'upright rock, pillar, column'), meaning 'without a pillar/column', in reference to the apparent stemless condition of some species in this genus. A genus of flowering plants native to New Zealand, Australia, South America, and various islands in the Pacific, Indian, and South Atlantic oceans. Learn more about Astelia.
nameBreakdown.species: nervōsa (Latin, adjective), meaning 'sinewy, nervous', in reference to the conspicuous veins on this species' leaves. Learn more about Astelia nervosa.

description: Ornamental, clump-forming plant with broad, spiky, silver-green leaves overlaid with red-bronze. Easily grown in full sun or semi-shade. Will tolerate both moist and dry sites. Dramatic in group plantings. Excellent in containers.

nameBreakdown.family: willow family, a family of flowering trees and shrubs. Learn more about Salicaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: azara (Latinised), named after the Spanish military officer, naturalist, and engineer, Félix de Azara (1746 - 1821). Some sources claim this genus was actually named after his older brother, José Nicolás de Azara (1730 - 1804), a Spanish diplomat. A genus of flowering evergreen shrubs and small trees. Learn more about Azara.
nameBreakdown.species: mīcrophylla (Latin, adjective), derived from the Greek adjective μικρός (mīkrós, 'small') and noun φύλλον (phúllon, 'leaf'), meaning 'small leaves', in reference to the size of this species' leaves. Learn more about Azara microphylla.

description: Has arching branches with small, glossy, dark-green leaves. Small, vanilla-scented, golden-yellow, spring flowers. Can be shaped into a dense screen. Branches can be espaliered.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of flowering plants predominantly distributed in the Southern Hemisphere. Learn more about Proteaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: banksia (Latinised), named in honour of the English naturalist and botanist, Joseph Banks (1743 - 1820). A genus of flowering trees and shrubs. Learn more about Banksia.
nameBreakdown.species: integrifolia (Latin, adjective), derived from the Latin adjective integer (entire, whole, undivided) and noun folium (leaf), meaning 'entire leaves', in reference to the entire leaf margins and undivided leaves of this species that are not divided or serrated. Learn more about Banksia integrifolia.

description: Upright-grower when younger, becoming more open with age. Quick-growing and coastal hardy. Large, yellow brush flowers from autumn through to spring attract tuis and bellbirds. Great for shelter. Can be pruned to any shape and size.

nameBreakdown.family: laurel family, a family of flowering trees and shrubs, occuring mainly in warm temperate and tropical regions, especially Southeast Asia and South America. Many are aromatic and evergreen, but some are deciduous. Learn more about Lauraceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: beilschmiedia (Latinised), named after the German pharmacist and botanist, Carl Traugott Beilschmied (1793 - 1848). A genus of trees and shrubs. Learn more about Beilschmiedia.
nameBreakdown.species: tarairi (Latinised), derived from the Te Reo Māori noun taraire, the name of this species in Te Reo Māori. Learn more about Beilschmiedia tarairi.

description: Stately, erect tree with smooth, brown bark. Young shoots are covered with fine, brown hairs. Broad, leathery, olive-green leaves are heavily-veined and glossy. Prefers moist soil and tolerates light to medium frosts. Wood pigeons adore the large, purple berries in autumn.

nameBreakdown.family: laurel family, a family of flowering trees and shrubs, occuring mainly in warm temperate and tropical regions, especially Southeast Asia and South America. Many are aromatic and evergreen, but some are deciduous. Learn more about Lauraceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: beilschmiedia (Latinised), named after the German pharmacist and botanist, Carl Traugott Beilschmied (1793 - 1848). A genus of trees and shrubs. Learn more about Beilschmiedia.
nameBreakdown.species: tawa (Latinised), derived from the Te Reo Māori noun tawa, the name of this species in Te Reo Māori. Learn more about Beilschmiedia tawa.

description: A slow-growing but enduring tree which ultimately becomes a forest giant. Erect-grower with almost black bark. The small, pale-green, willowy leaves hang in a graceful habit. Wood pigeons adore the large, purple berries in winter.

nameBreakdown.family: barberry family, a family of herbs, shrubs, and trees. Learn more about Berberidaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: berberis (Latin, noun), probably referring to species in this genus growing in Europe or specifically Spain. Possibly derived from the Arabic noun barbārīs (barberry). Commonly known as barberry, a genus of deciduous and evergreen shrubs. Learn more about Berberis.
nameBreakdown.species: thunbergii (Latinised), named after the Swedish naturalist Carl Peter Thunberg (1743 - 1828) who sent this species from Japan to Europe. Learn more about Berberis thunbergii.
nameBreakdown.form: ātropurpurea (Latin, adjective), meaning 'dark purple', in reference to the colour of this form's leaves.

description: Has rich, purple to red leaves which hold their colour throughout spring and summer, turning bright-red in fall. The tight column of upright stems needs no trimming to keep its form. Stems have very sharp thorns. Great for restricted sites.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: betula (Latin, noun), meaning 'birch tree'. Commonly known as birch, a genus of deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betula.
nameBreakdown.species: costāta (Latin, adjective), meaning 'ribbed', in reference to the prominent veins on this species' leaves. Learn more about Betula costata.

description: Has beautiful, peeling bark that is cream-white with pink-orange tones. Upright growth habit. Bright-green leaves with conspicuous veining. Golden autumn leaves. Does not tolerate drought.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: betula (Latin, noun), meaning 'birch tree'. Commonly known as birch, a genus of deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betula.
nameBreakdown.species: ermanii (Latinised), named after the German natural scientist who discovered this species, George Adolph Erman (1806 - 1877). Learn more about Betula ermanii.

description: A graceful, vigorous tree with peeling bark that is cream-white with pink-orange tones. This imparts a warm hue among darker evergreen trees, especially through the winter months. Bright-green leaves turn bright-yellow in autumn. Conical, upright-grower which broadens with age.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: betula (Latin, noun), meaning 'birch tree'. Commonly known as birch, a genus of deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betula.
nameBreakdown.species: ermanii (Latinised), named after the German natural scientist who discovered this species, George Adolph Erman (1806 - 1877). Learn more about Betula ermanii.

description: Pure-white trunked birch which has peeling bark. Green leaves turn butter-yellow in autumn.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: betula (Latin, noun), meaning 'birch tree'. Commonly known as birch, a genus of deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betula.
nameBreakdown.species: nigrā (Latin, adjective), meaning 'black, dark', in reference to the colour of the bark on mature trees of this species of this species. Learn more about Betula nigra.

description: One of the best trees for planting in wet areas. Has a strong, pyramidal form. Has peeling bark that on younger trees is pink to orange-brown and reveals lighter, cream-white bark when peeling. On older trees the bark is red to grey-brown developing to almost black. Glossy, green leaves are glaucous underneath. They turn bright-yellow in autumn.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: betula (Latin, noun), meaning 'birch tree'. Commonly known as birch, a genus of deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betula.
nameBreakdown.species: nigrā (Latin, adjective), meaning 'black, dark', in reference to the colour of the bark on mature trees of this species. Learn more about Betula nigra.

description: A graceful tree with pendant branches. Shiny, deep-green leaves turn yellow in autumn. Bears long, striking, male catkins in late winter. Has peeling bark that on younger trees is pink to orange-brown and reveals lighter, cream-white bark when peeling. On older trees the bark is red to grey-brown developing to almost black. Thrives in both moist and dry positions.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: betula (Latin, noun), meaning 'birch tree'. Commonly known as birch, a genus of deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betula.
nameBreakdown.species: nigrā (Latin, adjective), meaning 'black, dark', in reference to the colour of the bark on mature trees of this species. Learn more about Betula nigra.

description: Has gently-weeping, pendulous branches and pink, peeling bark. The foliage is dark-green throughout spring and summer, but takes on a striking yellow colour in autumn. Has peeling bark that on younger trees is pink to orange-brown and reveals lighter, cream-white bark when peeling. On older trees the bark is red to grey-brown developing to almost black.

description: This is a highly-rated birch for its prominent white trunk and graceful, pendulous young stems. The glossy, green leaves turn yellow in autumn. Lovely in group plantings.

nameBreakdown.species: pendula (Latin, adjective), meaning 'hanging, hanging down, pendant, suspended', in reference to the graceful, pendulous young stems of this species. Learn more about Betula pendula.

description: Narrow-growing tree with cascading, slender branches. The rich-purple leaf-colouring holds well throughout spring and summer. Young branches are purple-black. Has white bark, although less white than Betula pendula. Protect from strong winds.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: betula (Latin, noun), meaning 'birch tree'. Commonly known as birch, a genus of deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betula.
nameBreakdown.species: pendula (Latin, adjective), meaning 'hanging, hanging down, pendant, suspended', in reference to the graceful, pendulous young stems of this species. Learn more about Betula pendula.

description: Has the same graceful habit of the but with more cascading branches. The rich-green leaves are deeply-cut and serrated, giving the tree a light, dainty effect. White trunks are a feature on mature trees. Less tolerant of long dry spells. Yellow autumn leaves.

nameBreakdown.family: birch family, a family of mostly Northern Hemisphere deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betulaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: betula (Latin, noun), meaning 'birch tree'. Commonly known as birch, a genus of deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betula.
nameBreakdown.species: pendula (Latin, adjective), meaning 'hanging, hanging down, pendant, suspended', in reference to the graceful, pendulous young stems of this species. Learn more about Betula pendula.

description: A compact, upright birch with lime-green leaves through the summer. Brilliant gold autumn leaves. Branch stems are golden-orange, changing to pink-red through winter. Develops very white trunks. Excellent street tree.

description: Forms a dome of slender, side-branches which droop to the ground from a straight trunk. Small green leaves turn yellow in autumn.

nameBreakdown.variety: jāpōnica (Latin, adjective), meaning 'Japanese, of or relating to Japan', in reference to this species' native geographical location.

description: This lovely birch has a slender form like the, but with larger and more substantial leaves which turn bright-yellow in autumn. Very white bark right down to ground level is maintained into old age. Rust-resistant leaves.

nameBreakdown.genus: betula (Latin, noun), meaning 'birch tree'. Commonly known as birch, a genus of deciduous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Betula.
nameBreakdown.species: populifolia, derived from the Latin nouns pōpulus (poplar tree) and folia (leaf), meaning 'poplar-leaved', in reference to this species' leaves resembling those of the genus Populus. Learn more about Betula populifolia.

description: This is a grafted birch, so all trees grow uniform and identical. Very narrow-growing form. Great as a street tree, for avenues, or where space is limited. Dazzling white bark from ground level which is maintained into old age. Yellow autumn leaves.

Scented white flowers throughout summer. Self-fertile. Citrus x aurantiifolia is a hybrid between Citrus micrantha (syn. Citrus hystrix var. micrantha) and Citrus medica.

Bearss, who developed this seedless variety about 1895 in his nursery at Porterville, California. Citrus x latifolia is a hybrid between Citrus x aurantiifolia and Citrus x limon.

Citrus x meyeri is most likely a hybrid between Citrus medica and the hybrid formed between Citrus maxima and Citrus reticulata.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of flowering trees, shrubs, and herbs native to northern temperate regions and tropical Asia. Learn more about Cornaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: cornus (Latin, noun), meaning 'dogwood', originally referring to Cornus mas. The generic name could also be derived from the Latin noun cornūs (horn, power, strength), in reference to the high strength, density, and hardness of the wood of species in this genus. Commonly known as dogwood, a genus of flowering plants that are native throughout much of temperate and boreal Eurasia and North America, with China, Japan, and the southeastern United States being particularly rich in native species. Learn more about Cornus.

description: Upright-growing tree with tiered, semi-weeping branches. Large, flat, lime-green flowers age to white in late-spring. Small, red fruit in autumn until eaten by birds. Cornus 'Eddie's White Wonder' is a cross between Cornus nuttallii and Cornus florida, discovered by nurseryman Henry M. Eddie of Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada in 1945.

Commonly known as dogwood, a genus of flowering plants that are native throughout much of temperate and boreal Eurasia and North America, with China, Japan, and the southeastern United States being particularly rich in native species. Learn more about Cornus.
nameBreakdown.species: flōrida (Latin, adjective), meaning 'blooming, flowery, florid', in reference to the beautiful and many flowers produced by this species. Learn more about Cornus florida.

nameBreakdown.species: kousa, unknown meaning, first named by F. Buerger and then confirmed by the British diplomat Henry Fletcher Hance (1827 - 1886). The specific epithet is not the Japanese name for this species as many sources claim. The correct Japanese name for this species is yamaboushi, meaning 'mountain priest', in reference to the mound in the centre of the flower resembling the shaven head of a priest and the four white bracts that resemble the scarf worn by monk-soldiers on the ancient temple Enryaku-ji located on Mount Hiei, Japan. Learn more about Cornus kousa.

description: A vigorous grower and good producer of large nuts. Harvest red-orange to brown nuts in late-summer to early-autumn. Pollinators include Corylus avellana 'Butler', Corylus avellana 'Merveille de Bowillier', and Corylus avellana 'Tonda di Giffoni'.

description: Produces good crops of small, round nuts that are used mainly for processing. Harvest red-orange to brown nuts in late-summer to early-autumn. Pollinators include Corylus avellana 'Alexandra', Corylus avellana 'Auckland No. 2', and Corylus avellana 'Merveille de Bowillier'.

nameBreakdown.species: colurna (Latin, adjective), meaning 'of hazel', the classical name for this species.

description: Erect, conical-grower with a very symmetrical branching habit. Produces edible brown nuts in autumn, although they are encased in a thick, hard, green shell that makes them difficult to extract. Fruiting is irregular, occurring every two to three years. Tolerates hot, dry climates. Excellent street tree. Has corky bark. Yellow-green catkins from early-spring to early-summer are a source of pollen for bees. Yellow autumn leaves. Has a deep rooting system, and does not transplant well.

nameBreakdown.family: myrtle family, a family of evergreen trees and shrubs. Learn more about Myrtaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: corymbia, derived from the Latin noun corymbus (cluster of fruit or flowers), in reference to the flowers of species in this genus growing in a corymb. Commonly known as bloodwood and eucalypt, a genus of flowering trees that are native to Australia and New Guinea.
nameBreakdown.species: ficifolia, derived from the Latin nouns fīcus (fig) and folium (leaf), meaning 'fig-leaved', in reference to the similarity of this species' leaves to some species in the genus Ficus.

description: Sturdy, single-trunked tree with a round-headed, compact crown. Large, thick, green leaves. Flowers in mid-summer with variations of glowing red, orange, and pink. Flowers attract nectar-seeking birds. Tolerant of high rainfall, droughts, and coastal winds.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of flowering plants native to New Guinea, Australia, New Zealand, New Caledonia, and Vanuatu.
nameBreakdown.genus: corynocarpus, derived from the Greek nouns κορύνη (korúnē, 'mace, club') and καρπός (karpós, 'fruit'), meaning 'club fruit', in reference to the shape of the fruit of species in this genus. A genus of flowering plants native to New Guinea, Australia, New Zealand, New Caledonia, and Vanuatu.
nameBreakdown.species: laevigātus (Latin, adjective), meaning 'smooth, polished', in reference to the appearance and texture of the leaves of this species.

description: Handsome, upright-growing tree with large, glossy, leathery, deep-green leaves. Grows naturally alongside waterways. Tolerates moderate coastal winds, frosts once established, and dry conditions. Large, orange fruit in late summer are relished by wood pigeons.

nameBreakdown.family: cashew or sumac family, a family of flowering plants mostly native to tropical North America, South America, Africa, and India.
nameBreakdown.genus: cotinus (Latin, noun), meaning 'a shrub that gives or furnishes a purple colour', a name given by Pliny the Elder (AD 23/24 - 79) to a shrub growing in the Apennine Mountains, Italy from which the Romans extracted a purple dye. Pliny derived this name from the Greek noun κότινος (kótinos, 'wild olive tree [Olea europaea]'). Commonly known as smoke bush or smoketree, a genus of flowering large shrubs and small trees native to the warm temperate Northern Hemisphere.
nameBreakdown.species: coggygria, derived from the Greek noun κοκκυγέα (kokkūgéā), which is the Greek name for this species.

description: Lime and golden foliage throughout spring and summer, which lightens up dark areas and adds contrast. Beautiful autumn foliage of orange and red. If flowering does occur, it will be pink flower plumes on old wood in mid-summer. Best grown in part-shade. Keep moist.

Impressive heads of double crimson-red flowers smother the tree in late-spring. Produces red fruits in autumn that birds love. Excellent street tree. Doesn't develop any appreciable autumn colour. Branches have thorns. A very tough tree that will grow in almost all conditions. Crataegus x media is a hybrid between Crataegus monogyna and Crataegus laevigata.

nameBreakdown.species: capēnsis (Latin, adjective), meaning 'of or relating to the Cape Province [Cape Colony, Cape of Good Hope], South Africa', in reference to this species' native geographical location.

Does not have an invasive root system and can be grown in large pots.

description: Compact, pyramidal-growing conifer with smooth, frosted, blue leaves. Very amenable to pruning into any shape or form. Quick-growing and hardy to strong winds and drought. Makes an excellent dense shelter. Highly resistant to cypress canker.

nameBreakdown.hybrid: leylandii (Latinised), named in 1926 by the English botanist William Dallimore (1871 - 1959) and his associate, the British botanist and dendrologist Albert Bruce Jackson (1876 - 1947), in honour of Christopher Leyland who owned the estates in which this hybrid species was discovered.

description: Has light-green foliage. Grows with a narrow form and is lightly-branched. Great for shelter belts and hedges. Cupressus x leylandii is a hybrid between Hesperocyparis macrocarpa and Callitropsis nootkatensis.

description: Grows well in warmer areas. Very fast-growing tree with naturally wide-spreading branches. Can be easily pruned into a narrow dense screen. Always has fresh-green leaves which are soft to the touch. Tolerant of strong winds, but not coastal winds. Has better canker resistance than Cupressus x leylandii cultivars. Cupressus x ovensii is a hybrid between Callitropsis nootkatensis and Cupressus lusitanica.

description: A beautiful upright, columnar tree with green to blue-green foliage. Prefers hot, dry climates and well-drained soils. Drought tolerant once established.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of tree ferns.
nameBreakdown.genus: cyathea, derived from the Latin noun cyathus meaning 'a small ladle, beaker, or cup', in reference to the cup-shaped sori on the underside of the fronds of species in this genus. A genus of tree ferns that grow in habitats ranging from tropical rain forests to temperate woodlands.
nameBreakdown.species: cunninghamii (Latinised), named in honour of the English botanist and explorer Allan Cunningham (1791 - 1839), a plant collector for the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew in the United Kingdom who visited New Zealand in 1826.

description: A slender-trunked grower similar to Cyathea smithii, but when mature has a clean trunk as opposed to the skirt of dead frond stalks on the trunk of Cyathea smithii. Naturally grows in damp forest in stream gullies and riverbanks. Has a lower tolerance for drought than other tree fern species.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of tree ferns.
nameBreakdown.genus: cyathea, derived from the Latin noun cyathus meaning 'a small ladle, beaker, or cup', in reference to the cup-shaped sori on the underside of the fronds of species in this genus. A genus of tree ferns that grow in habitats ranging from tropical rain forests to temperate woodlands.
nameBreakdown.species: dealbāta (Latin, participle), meaning 'whitewashed', in reference to the distinctive silver-white undersides of the fronds of this species.

description: Easily distinguished by the silver-white undersides of mature fronds. Tolerates drier conditions once established, but should be protected from strong winds and frosts.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of tree ferns.
nameBreakdown.genus: cyathea, derived from the Latin noun cyathus meaning 'a small ladle, beaker, or cup', in reference to the cup-shaped sori on the underside of the fronds of species in this genus. A genus of tree ferns that grow in habitats ranging from tropical rain forests to temperate woodlands.
nameBreakdown.species: medullaris (Latin, adjective), meaning 'pithy, filled with pith or marrow', in reference to the pith of the trunk of this species that was cooked and eaten by Māori.

description: The tallest-growing of New Zealand's tree ferns. Has a distinctive, tall, black trunk. Prefers moisture-rich soil and shelter from wind. Can grow to 20m tall with up to 5m long fronds in ideal conditions.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of tree ferns.
nameBreakdown.genus: cyathea, derived from the Latin noun cyathus meaning 'a small ladle, beaker, or cup', in reference to the cup-shaped sori on the underside of the fronds of species in this genus. A genus of tree ferns that grow in habitats ranging from tropical rain forests to temperate woodlands.
nameBreakdown.species: smithii (Latinised), named in honour of the British botanist John Smith (1798 - 1888) who was the first curator at the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew in the United Kingdom.

description: The tree fern that is most tolerant of cold with fronds that are thin and soft in texture. Has a skirt of dead frond stalks on its trunk.

nameBreakdown.family: cycad family, a family of ancient plants that resemble palms and tree ferns.
nameBreakdown.genus: cycas, derived from the Greek noun κυκας (kukas), which is thought to be a transcription error for the Greek noun κόϊκας (kóïkas, 'palm tree [specifically Hyphaene thebaica]') that occured when a scribe was copying a work of Theophrastus. A genus of ancient plants that resemble palms and tree ferns.
nameBreakdown.species: revolūta (Latin, participle), meaning 'revolved, rolled', in reference to the leaflets of this species, which curl under.

description: Frost tender and slow-growing. Leaves are a deep, semi-gloss green and grow out into a feather-like rosette. Leaves have small protective barbs that must be avoided.

nameBreakdown.family: rose family, a family of mostly deciduous (but some evergreen), flowering herbs, shrubs, and trees. Learn more about Rosaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: cydonia, derived from the Greek name for an ancient city on Crete, Κυδωνία (Kudōnía), where a species in this genus grew. Commonly known as quince, a genus of flowering deciduous trees bearing edible fruit.
nameBreakdown.species: oblonga (Latin, adjective), meaning 'oblong', in reference to the shape of the fruit of this species.

description: An attractive fruiting tree with large, pale-green fruit. The skin is a soft yellow when ripe. The white flesh has a slight pineapple taste. Tastes best when cooked or mixed with other fruit. Hardy and tolerant, but happiest in the sun. Fruits from mid-autumn through to early-winter. Pink buds open to white flowers in mid to late-spring. Self-fertile.

nameBreakdown.family: rose family, a family of mostly deciduous (but some evergreen), flowering herbs, shrubs, and trees. Learn more about Rosaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: cydonia, derived from the Greek name for an ancient city on Crete, Κυδωνία (Kudōnía), where a species in this genus grew. Commonly known as quince, a genus of flowering deciduous trees bearing edible fruit.
nameBreakdown.species: oblonga (Latin, adjective), meaning 'oblong', in reference to the shape of the fruit of this species.

description: Popular selection from Turkey. Fruit is large, furrowed, oblong to pear-shaped, golden-yellow, and very aromatic. Flesh is mild, tender, and light-yellow. The fruit keeps very well. Moderately vigorous tree with unusually large leaves. Fruits from mid-autumn through to early-winter. Pink buds open to white flowers in mid to late-spring. Self-fertile.

nameBreakdown.family: rose family, a family of mostly deciduous (but some evergreen), flowering herbs, shrubs, and trees. Learn more about Rosaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: cydonia, derived from the Greek name for an ancient city on Crete, Κυδωνία (Kudōnía), where a species in this genus grew. Commonly known as quince, a genus of flowering deciduous trees bearing edible fruit.
nameBreakdown.species: oblonga (Latin, adjective), meaning 'oblong', in reference to the shape of the fruit of this species.

description: This disease-resistant quince was developed from an old tree growing at the Brown Sugar Cafe in Taihape. The aromatic, yellow-skinned fruit have lemon-coloured flesh. Tolerant, and easy to grow in a sunny spot. Use for making cider, jams, and preserves. Fruits from mid-autumn through to early-winter. Pink buds open to white flowers in mid to late-spring. Self-fertile.

nameBreakdown.family: podocarp family, a family of mainly Southern Hemisphere coniferous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Podocarpaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: dacrycarpus, derived from the Greek nouns δάκρυ (dákru, 'a tear') and καρπός (karpós, 'fruit'), meaning 'tear-shaped fruit', in reference to the shape of the fruit of species in this genus. A genus of coniferous trees and shrubs native to New Zealand, Fiji, New Caledonia, New Guinea, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, northern Myanmar and southern China.
nameBreakdown.species: dacrydioides, derived from the genus name Dacrydium and the Latin suffix oides (like, similar to), in reference to this species' similarity to species in the genus Dacrydium.

description: Handsome, narrow-growing tree with soft-green leaves on semi-weeping branches. Juvenile foliage is a brown colour before turning green. Prefers moist situations next to streams, lakes, and ponds. Yellow-green catkins in mid-spring to mid-summer are a source of pollen for bees. Produces orange-red fruit that grow under a purple-black seed from mid-summer to mid-autumn. Great source of food for birds.

nameBreakdown.family: podocarp family, a family of mainly Southern Hemisphere coniferous trees and shrubs. Learn more about Podocarpaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: dacrydium, derived from the Greek noun δάκρυ (dákru) meaning 'a tear', in reference to the exudation of small tear-shaped resin droplets from the wood. A genus of coniferous trees and shrubs native to New Zealand, New Caledonia, Fiji, the Solomon Islands, New Guinea, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Thailand, and southern China.
nameBreakdown.species: cupressinum (Latin, adjective), meaning 'of or relating to a cypress tree', in reference to this species supposedly resembling some species in the genus Cupressus.

description: A slow-growing tree easily accommodated in the home garden for at least fifty years. Juvenile trees have a pyramidal crown and pendulous branches, but acquire a round-topped crown with strong lateral branches bearing pendulous branchlets and foliage when mature. Foliage on juvenile trees may turn bronze during winter before returning to green in spring. Green catkins in mid-spring to mid-summer are a source of pollen for bees. Produces orange-red fruit that grow under a purple-black seed from mid-summer to mid-autumn. Seed is only set every few years.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of flowering evergreen shrubs and trees native to east and southeast Asia, the Indian Subcontinent, and New Guinea.
nameBreakdown.genus: daphniphyllum, derived from the Greek nouns δάφνη (dáphnē, 'sweet bay laurel [specifically Laurus nobilis]') and φύλλον (phúllon, 'leaf'), meaning 'bay-leaved', in reference to the leaves of some species in this genus resembling those of Laurus nobilis. A genus of flowering evergreen shrubs and trees native to east and southeast Asia, the Indian Subcontinent, and New Guinea.
nameBreakdown.species: macropodum, derived from the Greek adjective μακρός (makrós, 'long') and noun πούς (poús, 'foot, leg'), meaning 'long-footed, long-legged', in reference to the long stalks (petioles) of this species.

description: Has dark-green, glossy, rhododendron-like leaves that tend to droop in winter, revealing the bright-red leaf stalks on new growth. New spring growth is pale-green, often flushed with pink. Purple-pink male and pale-green female flowers are borne on separate plants in late-spring. Pollinated female plants produce blue-black berries in autumn.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of flowering trees.
nameBreakdown.genus: davidia (Latinised), named after the Catholic priest, zoologist, and botanist Armand David (1826 - 1900) who first described the species Davidia involucrata in 1869. A genus of flowering trees native to South Central and Southwest China.
nameBreakdown.species: involucrata, derived from the Latin noun involūcrum, meaning 'wrapper, covering, case', in reference to the large white bracts that surround the flower heads of this species.

description: Forms a stately specimen tree with robust branches and a rounded crown. Extraordinary flowers resemble white handkerchiefs which hang and flutter beneath the beautiful ribbed leaves in late-spring. Shelter from strong winds. Sometimes produces orange and red autumn colour.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of ferns that are found mostly in tropical regions of the Southern Hemisphere, but can be found as far south as southern New Zealand.
nameBreakdown.genus: dicksonia (Latinised), named after the Scottish nurseryman and botanist James Dickson (1738 - 1822). A genus of tree ferns found in Mexico, Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, Chile, Saint Helena, New Zealand, New Caledonia, Australia, Indonesia, New Guinea, and the Philippines.
nameBreakdown.species: fibrosa (Latin, adjective), meaning 'fibrous', in reference to the trunk of this species, which is protected by a thick layer of fibrous material.

description: Has a fibrous, rust-brown trunk which is often surrounded by a neat skirt of dead fronds. The living fronds form a dense crown. Prefers full-sun to part-shade. Keep moist while establishing and during dry spells.

nameBreakdown.family: a family of ferns that are found mostly in tropical regions of the Southern Hemisphere, but can be found as far south as southern New Zealand.
nameBreakdown.genus: dicksonia (Latinised), named after the Scottish nurseryman and botanist James Dickson (1738 - 1822). A genus of tree ferns found in Mexico, Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, Chile, Saint Helena, New Zealand, New Caledonia, Australia, Indonesia, New Guinea, and the Philippines.
nameBreakdown.species: squarrōsa (Latin, adjective), meaning 'rough', in reference to the rough fronds of this species.

description: One of the toughest tree ferns, tolerating some full-sun (not strong afternoon sun during the warmer months), drier soils, and light winds. Smaller leaf fronds than the Cyathea species of tree fern, so good for smaller gardens.

nameBreakdown.family: soapberry family, a family of flowering trees, lianas, and herbaceous plants that occur in many temperate and tropical regions. Learn more about Sapindaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: dodonaea (Latinised), named after the Flemish physician and botanist Rembert Dodoens (1517 - 1585), who has been referred to as the father of botany. Commonly known as hopbush, a genus of flowering shrubs and small trees native to tropical, subtropical, and warm temperate regions of Africa, the Americas, southern Asia, and Australasia.
nameBreakdown.species: viscōsa (Latin, adjective), meaning 'viscous, sticky', in reference to the young leaves of this species that are covered with a sticky secretion that hardens with age.

description: Quick-growing, upright tree, bushy to the ground. Long, narrow, pale-green leaves. Yellow-green to red-green flowers from late-winter to mid-summer. Very tough, tolerating sub-zero temperatures, salt-laden winds, drought, and polluted atmospheres. Excellent for screening and erosion control.

nameBreakdown.family: soapberry family, a family of flowering trees, lianas, and herbaceous plants that occur in many temperate and tropical regions. Learn more about Sapindaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: dodonaea (Latinised), named after the Flemish physician and botanist Rembert Dodoens (1517 - 1585), who has been referred to as the father of botany. nameBreakdown.species: viscōsa (Latin, adjective), meaning 'viscous, sticky', in reference to the young leaves of this species that are covered with a sticky secretion that hardens with age.

description: Quick-growing, upright tree, bushy to the ground. Long, narrow, purple-bronze leaves. Very tough, tolerating sub-zero temperatures, salt-laden winds, drought, and polluted atmospheres. Yellow-green to red-green flowers from late-winter to mid-summer.

nameBreakdown.family: grass family, a family of flowering annual and perennial herbs native to all continents of the world, including Antarctica.
nameBreakdown.genus: drepanostachyum, derived from the Greek nouns δρεπάνη (drepánē, 'sickle') and στάχυς (stákhus, 'an ear of grain'), in reference to the synflorescences (clusters of flowers) of species in this genus being shaped like a spike. Commonly known as bamboo, a genus of grasses native to China, Indochina, and the Indian Subcontinent.
nameBreakdown.species: falcātum (Latin, adjective), meaning 'curved, hooked, sickle-shaped', in reference to the sickle-shaped flowering branches of this species.

description: A dense, clump-forming bamboo. Has light-green foliage with long, arching canes. Prefers moist, well-drained soil. Shelter from strong winds.

nameBreakdown.family: mahogany family, a family of flowering trees, shrubs, and herbs. Learn more about Meliaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: dysoxylum, derived from the Greek prefix δυσ (dus, 'bad') and noun ξύλον (xúlon, 'wood'), meaning 'bad-smelling wood', in reference to the fetid odour of the wood of some species in this genus. A genus of flowering trees and shrubs native to New Guinea, eastern and northern Australia, New Caledonia, Fiji, Southeast Asia, southern China, the Indian subcontinent, the Philippines, Taiwan, the Caroline Islands, New Zealand, and Niue.
nameBreakdown.species: spectābile (Latin, adjective), meaning 'notable, admirable, remarkable', possibly in reference to the sweet-smelling flowers that sprout directly from the trunk and branches of this species.

description: A handsome upright tree, suited to coastal windy conditions but requiring good soil and shelter from frosts. Scented white flowers in panicles from early-autumn to mid-winter. Large glossy, green leaves.

nameBreakdown.family: oleaster family, a family of flowering shrubs and small trees native to temperate regions of the Northern Hemisphere, tropical Asia, and Australia.
nameBreakdown.genus: elaeagnus (Latinised), derived from the Greek noun ἐλαίαγνος (elaíagnos) used by Theophrastus (c. 371 - c. 287 BC) to describe a shrub (possibly Myrica gale or a species in the genus Myrica). Commonly know as silverberry or oleaster, a genus of flowering deciduous and evergreen shrubs and small trees mostly native to temperate and subtropical regions of Asia.
nameBreakdown.hybrid: submacrophylla, derived from the Latin preposition sub (under) and adjective macrophylla (large-leaved), in reference to this hybrid species having large-leaves, but ones that are slightly smaller than those of one of its parents, Elaeagnus macrophylla, due to the other parent, Elaeagnus pungens, having smaller leaves than Elaeagnus macrophylla.

description: Leaves are initially green, spotted with silver-grey, but mature to dark-green with silver-grey undersides. A tough, fast, bushy grower. Ideal for screening and hedging. Tolerates drought and salt-laden winds. Makes a very tough hedge. Grow in sun or shade. Produces very fragrant, sweet-scented, white flowers in autumn that are followed by orange berries in winter. Elaeagnus x submacrophylla is a hybrid between Elaeagnus macrophylla and Elaeagnus pungens.

nameBreakdown.family: rose family, a family of mostly deciduous (but some evergreen), flowering herbs, shrubs, and trees. Learn more about Rosaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: eriobotrya, derived from the Greek nouns ἔριον (érion, 'wool') and βότρυς (bótrus, 'bunch or cluster of grapes'), in reference to the wooly texture of the immature flowers that appear in clusters at the end of the branches of species in this genus. This can also refer to the fruit as sometimes the fruit of species in this genus have downy skin and they appear in clusters. A genus of mostly evergreen flowering shrubs and small trees native to woodland in the Himalayas and East Asia.
nameBreakdown.species: jāpōnica (Latin, adjective), meaning 'Japanese, of or relating to Japan', in supposed reference to this species' native geographical location, although this species is originally from China, it has been cultivated in Japan for about a millennium.

description: Clusters of small, white flowers in winter. Yellow-orange fruit ripens from early-spring to early-summer. Flavour is sweet-tart, similar to a plum or cherry. Prefers moist, well-drained soil in full-sun, but will tolerate partial shade. Drought-tolerant once established. Self-fertile.

nameBreakdown.family: rose family, a family of mostly deciduous (but some evergreen), flowering herbs, shrubs, and trees. Learn more about Rosaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: eriobotrya, derived from the Greek nouns ἔριον (érion, 'wool') and βότρυς (bótrus, 'bunch or cluster of grapes'), in reference to the wooly texture of the immature flowers that appear in clusters at the end of the branches of species in this genus. This can also refer to the fruit as sometimes the fruit of species in this genus have downy skin and they appear in clusters. A genus of mostly evergreen flowering shrubs and small trees native to woodland in the Himalayas and East Asia.
nameBreakdown.species: jāpōnica (Latin, adjective), meaning 'Japanese, of or relating to Japan', in supposed reference to this species' native geographical location, although this species is originally from China, it has been cultivated in Japan for about a millennium.

description: Coastal-hardy tree with yellow-orange skinned, yellow-fleshed, easy to peel, sweet fruit reminiscent of apricots in early summer. Excellent for large containers. Well suited to gardens of all sizes. Self-fertile.

nameBreakdown.family: myrtle family, a family of evergreen trees and shrubs. Learn more about Myrtaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: eucalyptus, derived from the Greek prefix εὐ (eu, 'good, well') and verb καλύπτω (kalúptō, 'to cover, conceal'), meaning 'well-covered', in reference to the operculum (protective cap-like structure) that covers the unopened flower buds. Commonly known as eucalypt, a genus of flowering trees, shrubs, and mallees, mostly native to Australia.
nameBreakdown.species: cinerea (Latin, adjective), meaning 'ash-coloured, grey', in reference to the white, waxy bloom on the foliage, flower buds, and fruit of this species.

description: Attractive ornamental and shelter tree. Rounded silvery blue-green leaves on juvenile trees. Mature trees have long leaves. Tolerates dry soils and coastal exposure.

nameBreakdown.family: myrtle family, a family of evergreen trees and shrubs. Learn more about Myrtaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: eucalyptus, derived from the Greek prefix εὐ (eu, 'good, well') and verb καλύπτω (kalúptō, 'to cover, conceal'), meaning 'well-covered', in reference to the operculum (protective cap-like structure) that covers the unopened flower buds. Commonly known as eucalypt, a genus of flowering trees, shrubs, and mallees, mostly native to Australia.
nameBreakdown.species: crēnulāta (Latin, adjective), meaning 'having round or blunt teeth on its margin', in reference to the scalloped (having an edge or border marked with semicircles) leaf margins of this species.

description: Has attractive, silver, egg-shaped to heart-shaped leaves with serrated edges that are used widely in cut-flower arrangements. Clusters of cream-white flowers in spring. Grows well in both wet and dry conditions.

nameBreakdown.family: myrtle family, a family of evergreen trees and shrubs. Learn more about Myrtaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: eucalyptus, derived from the Greek prefix εὐ (eu, 'good, well') and verb καλύπτω (kalúptō, 'to cover, conceal'), meaning 'well-covered', in reference to the operculum (protective cap-like structure) that covers the unopened flower buds. Commonly known as eucalypt, a genus of flowering trees, shrubs, and mallees, mostly native to Australia.
nameBreakdown.species: johnstonii (Latinised), named after the Scottish-Australian statistician and scientist Robert Mackenzie Johnston (1843 - 1918).

description: Thick, dark-green leaves. Has distinctive yellow-green bark. Will grow in wet areas and can tolerate drought. Fast-growing.

nameBreakdown.family: myrtle family, a family of evergreen trees and shrubs. Learn more about Myrtaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: eucalyptus, derived from the Greek prefix εὐ (eu, 'good, well') and verb καλύπτω (kalúptō, 'to cover, conceal'), meaning 'well-covered', in reference to the operculum (protective cap-like structure) that covers the unopened flower buds. Commonly known as eucalypt, a genus of flowering trees, shrubs, and mallees, mostly native to Australia.
nameBreakdown.species: leucoxylon, derived from the Greek adjective λευκός (leukós, 'white') and noun ξύλον (xúlon, 'wood'), meaning 'white wood', in reference to the colour of the bark of this species.

description: One of the hardiest gums, tolerating extreme drought and cold conditions. Adult leaves are long and grey-green. A profusion of deep-pink to red flowers hang from the branches from autumn into winter and are a valuable nectar supply for tuis, bellbirds, and wax-eyes. Tall, erect grower.

nameBreakdown.family: myrtle family, a family of evergreen trees and shrubs. Learn more about Myrtaceae.
nameBreakdown.genus: eucalyptus, derived from the Greek prefix εὐ (eu, 'good, well') and verb καλύπτω (kalúptō, 'to cover, conceal'), meaning 'well-covered', in reference to the operculum (protective cap-like structure) that covers the unopened flower buds. nameBreakdown.family: an ancient family of trees.
nameBreakdown.genus: ginkgo, a misspelling of the Japanese noun ginkyō, the Japanese name for Ginkgo biloba. This misspelling was first transcribed by the German naturalist, physician, and explorer Engelbert Kaempfer (1651 - 1716) in his book Amoenitatum Exoticarum. He was the first Westerner to see the species Ginkgo biloba. The misspelling was then included by Carl Linnaeus (1707 - 1778) in his book Mantissa Plantarum Altera, and the misspelling stuck as the generic name. A genus of non-flowering seed plants native to China.
nameBreakdown.species: biloba (Latin, adjective), meaning 'bilobate [having two lobes]', in reference to the leaves of this species usually being deeply-grooved in the middle, producing two distinct lobes.

description: Hardy tree of great beauty. Distinctive leaves are shaped like sections of maidenhair fern. In autumn, the leaves turn bright-gold over many weeks before falling to create a carpet of gold. Allow space for this tree to develop.

description: Very graceful tree with slender, branches, forming an erect columnar shape. Pointed green leaves are purple underneath. Large clusters of star-shaped, fragrant, white flowers almost obscure the branches in late-summer to autumn. Excellent for rapid screening.

Has an erect and graceful open form. Very fast-grower. Glossy, dark-green leaves. Clusters of honey-scented, yellow, tubular flowers are borne from late-spring through summer. Tolerant of dry and windy conditions. Ideal for the smaller garden.

Has a tiered horizontal branch structure and a broad crown. Produces red berries in autumn but requires Idesia polycarpa 'Male' for pollination. Both male and female forms produce small, yellow-green flowers in summer. Yellow autumn leaves.

Has a tiered horizontal branch structure and a broad crown. Handsome heart-shaped leaves. Both male and female forms produce small, yellow-green flowers in summer. Yellow autumn leaves. Pollinator for Idesia polycarpa 'Female'.
Upright, pyramidal form with spineless leaves. Clusters of red berries through winter. Excellent for screening and hedges. Trims into any shape.

images.alt: ilex x altaclerensis hendersonii foliage berries

description: Narrow, columnar-growing with small, dark-green, spineless leaves. Great as a screen which doesn't need side pruning. Excellent for containers and to use as focal points in the contemporary garden.

images.alt: ilex crenata sky pencil single tree
ilex crenata sky pencil young trees

description: Dark-green foliage. Upright, bushy grower. Great for topiary and hedging. Easy to trim into shapes. Best in full sun.

Dark, blue-green, soft, spiny leaves with purple-black stems. A slow, dense, upright grower. Profusion of small, white blossoms in summer. Plant in combination with pollinator Ilex x meserveae 'Blue Prince' to attain scarlet red berries in autumn. Tolerates semi-shade and cold conditions.

images.alt: ilex x meserveae blue angel berries
ilex x meserveae blue angel flowers
ilex x meserveae blue angel foliage
ilex x meserveae blue angel hedge

description: Dark, blue-green, spiny leaves and purple-black stems are a feature of this slow, dense, bushy grower. A profusion of small, white summer flowers. Grow as a companion pollinator to Ilex x meserveae 'Blue Angel'. Excellent hedging plant. Tolerates semi-shade and cold conditions.

images.alt: ilex x meserveae blue prince foliage

description: This is a tree for warm, sunny climates with no frosts. Soft, ferny leaves cover the spreading branches which radiate from the single trunk. Large, lavender-blue, trumpet-like flowers are borne in racemes in spring and early-summer. Excellent shade tree.

nameBreakdown.species: nigrā (Latin, adjective), meaning 'black, dark'.

description: A fast-growing tree with a tall, straight trunk and a wide, spreading head. Has dark-brown to black bark. Walnuts ripen in autumn. They are edible and have a desirable taste, but are much harder to extract than walnuts produced by Juglans regia. Self-fertile. The wood is highly-valued for commercial purposes such as furniture.

A slow-growing tree with a wide-spreading, rounded head. Great tree for paddock planting. Easy to crack walnuts are produced in autumn around fifteen years from planting. Yellow-green catkins in late-spring to early-summer are a source of pollen for bees. Self-fertile, but better crops when planted with another walnut variety like Juglans regia 'Meyric', Juglans regia 'Shannon', or Juglans regia 'Wilson's Wonder'.

New Zealand Tree Crops Association selection. Large walnuts. Prefers free-draining soil. Produces walnuts from about five years of age. Brown nuts are held in a green husk. Self-fertile, but better crops when planted with another walnut variety like Juglans regia 'Shannon' or Juglans regia 'Wilson's Wonder'.

A top-quality walnut bearing large crops of well-flavoured nuts. Easy to crack. Prefers free-draining soils. Produces walnuts from about five years of age. Brown nuts are held in a green husk. Self-fertile, but better crops when planted with another walnut variety like Juglans regia 'Meyric' or Juglans regia 'Wilson's Wonder'.

An old English variety that is vigorous and bears from a young age. Large thin-shelled nuts are sweetly-flavoured. Prefers free-draining soil. Produces walnuts from about three years of age. Brown nuts are held in a green husk. Self-fertile, but better crops when planted with another walnut variety like Juglans regia 'Meyric' or Juglans regia 'Shannon'.

nameBreakdown.species: chinēnsis (Latin, adjective), meaning 'Chinese, of or relating to China', in reference to this species' native geographical location.

description: Bright-green leaves in dense clusters cover the long, gracefully-curving branches growing out at all angles. An architectural focal point. Tolerates strong winds.
Narrow-growing, columnar conifer with blue-grey foliage. Good as a screen or windbreak. Drought tolerant once established. Seldom needs pruning.

Poplar-like tree with a narrow columnar form. Ideal for restricted areas where height is required. Large, long, leathery leaves are heavily-serrated. Red flowers in early-summer attract nectar-seeking birds. Tolerates poor soils, light frosts, and strong winds. Excellent street tree.

Has an open, spreading form clothed in pinnate leaves. Soft-pink spring leaves mature green and then turn yellow in autumn. Panicles of golden-yellow flowers in early-summer are followed by dangling, rose-red, papery capsules. Grows best in hot summers and cold winters. Excellent street tree.

Small, narrow, dark-green, aromatic, soft leaves and sprays of white flowers glisten on the bushes in early-summer. Very tough, tolerating frosts, drought, and poor soils. Excellent for screening or sheltering more tender plants. Attracts bees.

nameBreakdown.species: rōbusta (Latin, adjective), meaning 'robust, strong', in reference to the stature of the mature trees of this species.

description: Small, narrow, dark-green, aromatic, soft leaves and sprays of white flowers glisten on the bushes in early-summer. Very tough, tolerating frosts, drought, and poor soils. Excellent for screening or sheltering more tender plants. Attracts bees.
Weeping tree with beautiful golden-yellow blossoms in late-spring. Grows best with full sun in soil that won't dry out over summer. Can be grown over an archway.
Has a compact, rounded head. Fragrant racemes of yellow flowers hang from the branches in late-spring. Branches are pliable enough to train over high arches. Sets no seeds. Excellent street tree.

Soft, blue-green leaves turn yellow and orange in autumn before dropping. The bare red-brown branches on young trees are a winter feature. Very amenable to pruning and shaping. Makes an excellent container plant.

A slow-growing, handsome tree with a dense, bushy habit and columnar form for many decades. Glossy, deep-green leaves have serrated edges and complement the red new stems. Will fit into the home garden easily. Site on the edge of ponds and streams as it loves a moist position. Small, green-white flowers from mid-spring to early-summer.

A famous tree from the Mediterranean. Forms a compact, pyramidal shape with leathery, dark-green leaves, used for flavouring food. Very amenable to pruning and shaping into any form. Can make a dense, aromatic hedge. Excellent for coastal gardens.

Forms a compact, pyramidal shape with leathery leaves used for flavouring food. New leaves are golden-yellow, fading to green. Very amenable to pruning and shaping into any form. Can make a dense, aromatic hedge. Excellent for coastal gardens.

Differs from Laurus nobilis in that it has narrow, willow-like leaves. A famous tree from the Mediterranean. Forms a compact, pyramidal shape with leathery, dark-green leaves, used for flavouring food. Very amenable to pruning and shaping into any form. Can make a dense, aromatic hedge. A columnar-growing selection of bay tree. Great for narrow spaces. A famous tree from the Mediterranean with leathery, dark-green leaves, used for flavouring food. Very amenable to pruning and shaping into any form. Can make a dense, aromatic hedge. Excellent for coastal gardens.

Quick-growing tree with red young stems. Small, bronze-purple leaves smother the arching branches. Can be pruned to form a dense, colourful shelter or screen. A profusion of single, white flowers in summer. Very hardy, tolerant of drought conditions.

Makes an excellent screen or shelter. Fast-growing and very hardy, tolerating hot dry soils and cold temperatures. The bushes are smothered with a profusion of single, white flowers from spring. These are much loved by bees. Aromatic foliage.
A beautiful display of double, red-pink flowers in spring and summer.
A beautiful display of double, crimson-red flowers in late-winter and spring. New foliage is red-purple, fading to a deep-green.

description: Produces a vibrant display of red flowers in spring, completely covering the bush. Plant in a sunny location. Great for dry, exposed areas and coastal locations.
A beautiful display of single, pink flowers in spring and summer. Has purple-green foliage.
Produces single, pink flowers in spring.

Small, red-green leaves cover this dense, bushy grower. The flower buds are a feature over winter before bursting into bright, crimson-red, double-blossoms which smother the bush over an extended period in spring. Hardy for well-drained, sunny position.

Bears large, single, crimson flowers in spring. These contrast well with the beautiful, purple-red foliage. Hardy tree that prefers full sun with free-draining soil. Frost and drought tolerant once established.

Small, bright-green leaves cover this dense, bushy grower. The flower buds are a feature over winter before bursting into bright-red, double-blossoms which smother the bush over an extended period in spring. Hardly any seeds form. Hardy for well-drained sunny positions.
Handsome, symmetrical, pyramidal tree with bright-green, scale-like leaves. Superb as a neat-growing screen, for breaking up dark greenery, or for lining driveways.

A Chinese species with large, three-lobed leaves. Rich, purple-bronze new spring leaves. Autumn leaves are gorgeous apricot-orange and yellow. They persist on the tree well into winter. Smooth bark. Dense, conical growth habit.

Forms a stately, pyramidal tree with well-spaced branches and rugged, corky bark. Handsome, shining, five to seven-lobed, maple-shaped leaves. A riot of red, orange, yellow, and purple autumn leaves over a long period. Colours well in all climates. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind.

Selected clone with a narrow, pyramidal form when young, broadening with age. Larger maple-shaped leaves which emerge earlier than other varieties. Rich, red-burgundy autumn leaves which persist well into winter. Colours well in all climates. Excellent street tree. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind.

An Australian variety. Has smooth bark and a brilliant autumn display of red, purple, yellow, and orange, lasting well into winter in warmer areas. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind.

Has large green leaves broadly-margined with gold. During autumn, the leaves take on glowing pink and burgundy hues. Round-headed tree, ideal for the smaller garden. Colours well in all climates. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind.

Forms a dense, rounded ball of maple-shaped leaves. Autumn leaves in purple, orange, yellow, and red that persist well into winter. Excellent street tree. Great for formal planting. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind. Does not produce seed capsules.

Has a neat, pyramidal growth habit with smooth bark. Distinctive, rich crimson-red autumn leaves. Reliably colours every year regardless of the climatic conditions. Excellent street tree. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind.

description: A selection from Lees Road in Feilding. Colours early and holds colourful crimson-red leaves on until early winter. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind.

A dwarf selection. Narrow, upright growth habit with smaller, finer leaves. They turn a brilliant crimson in autumn and these hold well on the trees through winter. Tolerates moist and clay soil conditions. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind.

Autumn colour is a glowing burgundy-red. Does not set seed. Colours well in all climates. Excellent street tree. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind.

Upright, pyramidal form with outer branches that gracefully droop. The maple-shaped leaves are finely-cut and deeply-lobed. Striking autumn leaves are purple, red, orange, and yellow. In dry soil, produces a taproot that helps reinforce it against wind, but in wetter soil, only grows superficial roots and cannot tolerate much wind.
